Explanation of examples:
------------------------

The example01_* series all use the same physical system — Ni/Mg substitutions in a 2×2×2
supercell of rocksalt MgO (space group Fm-3m) — and illustrate how to generate input
files for five different calculators using the same INSOD file (apart from the FILER value).

- example01:

- FILER1_gulp:      Ni/Mg in MgO rocksalt, GULP (FILER=1). 4 Ni substitutions (nsubs=4) in
                    32 Mg sites. Uses catlow.lib (Buckingham potentials with core-shell model
                    for Ni and O2). Demonstrates the library directive and sod_type_map (the
                    SOD species O maps to the GULP type O2 in the library).

- FILER2_lammps:    Same system, LAMMPS (FILER=2). 4 Ni substitutions (nsubs=4). Demonstrates
                    the template_in.lammps file with sod_type_map lines and core-shell
                    representation in conf.data.

- FILER11_vasp:     Same system, VASP (FILER=11). 4 Ni substitutions. SOD generates POSCAR
                    files; the user must supply INCAR, KPOINTS and POTCAR.

- FILER12_castep:   Same system, CASTEP (FILER=12). 4 Ni substitutions. Demonstrates the
                    template_castep.cell file. The user must supply the .param file.

- FILER13_QE:       Same system, Quantum ESPRESSO (FILER=13). 4 Ni substitutions. Demonstrates
                    the template_pw.in file. Replace Ni.upf, Mg.upf, O.upf with your own
                    pseudopotential files before running.

- example02:         Al/Fe substitution in magnetite Fe3O4 (1×1×1 cubic spinel unit cell,
                    space group Fd-3m). Al substitutions from 0 to 16 across 24 mixed-occupancy
                    Fe sites (8 tetrahedral + 16 octahedral) are enumerated (FILER=-1); the
                    n04/ folder contains the OUTSOD for the 4-substitution case (99 inequivalent
                    configurations). The complexity arises because the substituted species (Fe)
                    occupies two structurally distinct sites.

- example03:         Fe/Sb disorder in a 2×2×2 supercell of rutile FeSbO4 (space group P4_2/mnm).
                    Starting from a generic MO2 parent structure, 8 M(IV) sites are replaced
                    by equal numbers of Fe(III) and Sb(V), giving 180 inequivalent configurations
                    out of a total of 12870 (FILER=-1; no calculation input files generated).
                    The OUTSOD is pre-computed in n08/.
                    See Grau-Crespo et al. Chem. Mater. 2004:
                    https://pubs.acs.org/doi/abs/10.1021/cm035271y

- example04:         Al/Fe substitution in a 2×2×2 supercell of LaFeO3 perovskite (space group
                    Pnma). 4 Al substitutions in 8 Fe sites give 6 inequivalent configurations.
                    GULP input files (FILER=1) using the Bush et al. potential (inline in
                    template_input.gin). The x250 folder provides an INGC file for
                    grand-canonical analysis (x=0.25); ENERGIES files are not pre-committed
                    and must be obtained by running GULP on the generated configurations.

- example05:         Zr/Sn substitution in the La2Sn2O7–La2Zr2O7 solid solution (pyrochlore,
                    space group Fd-3m, 1×1×1 unit cell). INSOD enumerates all compositions
                    (nsubs=0:16, FILER=-1): 17 levels from pure La2Sn2O7 (n00) to pure
                    La2Zr2O7 (n16), giving 1, 1, 3, 8, 22, ... 1 inequivalent configurations.
                    To generate CASTEP input files, change FILER=12 and set nsubs to the
                    desired level; pre-generated examples for nsubs=2 are in n02/c1-c3/.
                    The n00–n16 folders also contain pre-computed DFT results (ENERGIES,
                    DATA, SPECTRA, XSPEC) provided to demonstrate post-processing: canonical
                    statistics (sod_stat.sh) and grand-canonical NMR spectra averaging
                    (sod_gcstat.sh) with stress-volume correction. See x250 and x750.

- example06:         Li/Mg substitution coupled with an H vacancy in a 2×2×2 supercell of
                    rutile MgH2 (space group P4_2/mnm, #136). The charge-neutral defect pair
                    Li+/H-vacancy is enumerated as a multi-species substitution: sptarget: 1 2,
                    nsubs: 1 (Li on Mg), 1 (%H vacancy). 9 inequivalent configurations from
                    512 total (16 Mg x 32 H). VASP input files (FILER=11) generated; INCAR,
                    KPOINTS and POTCAR must be supplied by the user.

- example07:         Fe vacancies in maghemite (gamma-Fe2O3) starting from the P4(3)32 cubic
                    structure (space group 212, a=8.344 A). A 1×1×3 supercell has 12 vacant
                    Fe sites; SOD fills 4 of them with Fe (leaving 8 vacancies = gamma-Fe2O3
                    stoichiometry). 29 inequivalent configurations out of C(12,4)=495.
                    Demonstrates the %NAME vacancy syntax. GULP input files (FILER=1) using
                    catlow.lib.

- example08:         Methylammonium (MA = CH3NH3+) substitution in a 4×4×4 supercell of cubic
                    CsPbI3 perovskite (Pm-3m, 320 atoms). 2 of the 64 Cs A-sites are replaced
                    by MA molecules, yielding 9 inequivalent configurations. Demonstrates the
                    @NAME molecule syntax (@MA in newsymbol) with MA.xyz geometry. LAMMPS
                    data files (FILER=2) are generated; each conf.data has 334 atoms.

- example09:         Multi-species example: simultaneous Mg/La substitution (2 sites) and O vacancy
                    (1 site) in a 2×2×2 supercell of LaFeO3 perovskite. Two target sites are
                    specified (sptarget: 1 3) with nsubs on two lines: 2 (site 1), 1 (site 2).
                    Configurations are enumerated jointly under the full crystal symmetry
                    and written to n02_01/. FILER=-1.

- example10:         Ti_{50}Zr_{25}Nb_{25} (Ti_2ZrNb) alloy with biomedical interest (multi-nary).
                    Two species, Zr (4 atoms) and Nb (4 atoms), substitute Ti in a 2×2×2
                    supercell of the BCC structure (16 atoms total). No output files
                    requested (FILER=-1).

- example11:         Multi-nary example with three new species: equimolar NiCoFeCr Cantor
                    subsystem alloy in a 2×2×2 supercell of the FCC primitive cell (8 atoms
                    total: 2 Co, 2 Fe, 2 Cr, 2 Ni). Uses 225_primitive.sgo operators.
                    nsubs: 2 2 2. Out of 2520 total arrangements, 23 are inequivalent under
                    the full FCC symmetry. GULP input files are generated (FILER=1) using
                    an OpenKIM EAM potential (kim_model directive).

- example12:         Multi-species example: complex perovskite La0.75Sr0.25Mn0.25Fe0.75O3
                    in a 2x2x2 supercell (space group Pm-3m). Two target sites substituted
                    simultaneously: 2 Sr on 8 La-sites (binary, site 1) and 2 Mn on 8
                    Fe-sites (binary, site 2). nsubs on two lines: 2 (site 1), 2 (site 2).
                    13 inequivalent configurations from 784 total. FILER=-1.

- example13:         Multi-species example with 3 targets: La_{1-x}Sr_x Fe_{1-y}Mn_y O_{3-z}
                    in a 2x2x2 supercell of the Pm-3m perovskite (8 La, 8 Fe, 24 O sites).
                    One substitution per site: Sr on La, Mn on Fe, O vacancy (%O syntax).
                    sptarget: 1 2 3; nsubs on three lines: 1, 1, 1.
                    6 inequivalent configurations from 1536 total. FILER=-1.

- example14:         Multi-target multi-nary example: La_{1-x-y}Sr_{x}Ba_{y}Mn_{z}Fe_{1-z}O_3
                    in a 2x2x2 supercell of the Pm-3m perovskite.
                    Target 1 (8 La sites): ternary — 1 Sr + 1 Ba (nsubs line 1: "1 1").
                    Target 2 (8 Fe sites): binary — 1 Mn (nsubs line 2: "1").
                    3 inequivalent configurations from 448 total. FILER=-1.

